data.content:
In xUnit:

- **`[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]`** → **constructor** / **`IDisposable.Dispose()`** (xUnit creates a new instance per test)
- **`[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]`** → a **class fixture** implementing `IDisposable`, shared via `IClassFixture<T>`

Here's the converted class:

```csharp
// Shared fixture replaces [OneTimeSetUp] / [OneTimeTearDown]
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp] — runs before each test
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // Dispose replaces [TearDown] — runs after each test
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**
- `IClassFixture<T>` — xUnit injects one shared instance across all tests in the class (same lifetime as `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]`)
- Constructor/`Dispose` run per-test because xUnit creates a **new class instance for every test**
- If you need to share state across **multiple test classes**, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` with a `[Collection]` attribute instead
